## 4. The "Hand Feel" Experience

- Impact Sensation
    - Hardness Words: Firm, dense, yet uniquely springy. (44 degrees on Butterfly's scale).
    - Feedback: Slightly muted. The ultra-thick sponge absorbs a lot of vibration, preventing it from reaching the blade handle.
    - Hold vs. Release: Rapid release. The ball feels like it sinks into the sponge and is instantly violently ejected.
    - Dwell Time: Perceived as quite short due to the fast ejection speed, though the grip itself is extremely solid.

- Sound/Click: Subdued and hard. It lacks the crisp, metallic "click" of Tenergy 05, sounding slightly more muffled because of the thicker sponge.

---

## 5. Compatibility & Setup Guide

- Best Blade Matches
    - Outer Carbon: Best for elite players who want maximum, overwhelming speed and have the technique to control the extreme bounce (e.g., Viscaria, Fan Zhendong ALC).
    - Inner Carbon: Highly recommended. Blades like the Innerforce Layer ALC or Harimoto ALC help tame the bounciness and restore some dwell time and feeling.
    - All-Wood: Good for offensive all-wood blades to maximize spin while keeping the speed manageable for semi-pros.
    - Mismatch Cases: Fast, stiff composite blades (like Super ZLC) in the hands of amateur players—this will result in an uncontrollable, rocket-like setup.

- Forehand vs. Backhand Recommendation
    - Forehand: Exceptional for forehand-dominant players who step back and engage in powerful mid-distance rallies.
    - Backhand: Usable, especially for aggressive punch-blockers and chiquita users, but the short game can be very difficult to manage on the backhand side.

